11. Anterodorsal extension of anepimeron: (0) flat, (1) with posterior bump (
Fig. 18A–H
).

13. Meron: (0) relatively small, equal in height and width, (1) enlarged, much higher than wide (
Fig. 20A–F
).

14. Katepisternum: (0) pruinose, (1) mostly bare (
Fig. 21A–F
).

15. Anterior spiracle: (0) ovoid or reniform, (1) small, round, (2) large, round (
Fig. 22A–F
).

16. Posterior margin of anepisternum appearing: (0) ‘peeled back’, (1) folded partly over anterior bump (
Fig. 23A–F
). This area of the thorax is discussed above, in the overview of the evolution of thoracic structure.

17. Lateral parapsidal suture (suture between scutum and pleuron) and lateral ridge of scutum: (0) straight, extended anteriorly over spiracle, (1) with only short vestige of carina ending near to spiracle, (2) stopping well posterior of anterior spiracle and joining pronotal suture (
Fig. 24A–F
).

18. Metepimeron: (0) sclerotized, recognizable, broad, (1) reduced to at most narrow edge along posteri- or margin of meron (
Fig. 25A–F
).

The plesiomorphic condition of this sclerite can be seen in most schizophoran families (
Figs 1–3
, 
25A
), in which the metepimeron is considerably smaller than other sclerites, but is present. Within the phorids, the sciadocerines have a considerably well-developed metepimeron (
Figs 4
, 
25B
). In the euphorids, including the chonocephalines (
Fig. 25C
), the metepimeron is sometimes hardly recognizable as an independent sclerite, with only the suture posterior to the metepimeron being visible (
Fig. 25D–F
). In some cases, a slender sclerite can be seen.

19. Halter and posterior spiracle position: (0) closer to midpoint between wing base and dorsal margin of hind coxa, (1) close to wing base (
Fig. 26A–F
).

20. Katepisternum: (0) straight across top, (1) projected into anepimeron (
Fig. 27A–F
).
